The Ukrainian parliament refused, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph on the conviction of Julia Tymoshenko, the leader of the opposition.
The MPs refused at second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing the penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the currently imprisoned former Prime Minister.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to 7 years in prison in October for having reached a pre-distinctive agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must decide on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymoshenko describes the judgement of political vengeance of the regime and has caused a process of suspicion of bias of the court also to the west.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 members of parliament.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
