How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly to the countries of the Socialist bloc, because the trips to the West were very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimean and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (the two in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination for the West and the trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the Socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, a letter of invitation was required, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, it was necessary to tail all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The foreign exchange agreement that was the condition to travel to the west was denied "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs spent most of their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The journeys of the Czechs have since had a great revolution.
Although the holidays in Eastern Germany and Bulgaria were at their maximum until 1989, the Czechs spent 4 million holiday days abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox we do not know today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in neighbouring Western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel by plane to the west for a long time that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a journey from Czechs was at this time to take away his own food preserved, saucison, etc... to save.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists after decades of freely buying Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased, which has led to another important moment around 1997.
With increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 started to prepare tours with air charter connections that through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
In the late 1990s the Czechs had visa-free links with almost most developed countries all over the world, apart from the EU, which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters bring Czech tourists to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
It is more than 100,000 Czechs who visit the exotic countries each year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutional development, arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU deleted visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully fit into the developed group.
Also in 2008 Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for vacations abroad including ancillary expenses. Crowns per person.
