New York Congressman Anthony Weiner's celebrity and Internet-based celebrity, has been considered an idiot by quickly issuing unfutable evidence to contradict the accusations.
The former candidate for President John Edwards was accused of violations of the funding of campaigns related to the coverage of an extra-marriage relationship.
And then, none of those who have lived the story will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term of office about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave test responses to students to check out their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we face?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential competence that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game like, let's say, charades, where the aim is to write: "I have had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about the lie have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don't always begat, shout or act.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to detect.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, the formation of the question and the time of response.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge of deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are able to read others properly, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "centred on them" while women say more lies "centred on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - than married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if anyone is lying?
First, observe the normal behaviour of your subject.
That's what we call establishing benchmarks.
This helps provide a point of reference to measure future changes.
Watch the posture of your subject, laugh, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally puts their feet in a permanent position so as not to make unfair accusations when you see them put their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for indications of verbal and non-verbal misleading behaviours.
Consider these clues to be red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a shift of posture when all the difficult questions are gone.
The interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is just finished to seek trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson skipped using the past while claiming his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use a far-reaching language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or simply repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "woody language" in his answer to a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember property... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances for anyone to avoid victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
