Analysis of the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to PREP data, the difference between the first and second place in the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of the count "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the election trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data shown by the Program of Preliminary Electoral Results (PREP), the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without accounting for the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, in the past 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal reform of electoral matters.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not approve either its Political Constitution or its Electoral Code of State or its Electoral Justice Act, at the same time that the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period for this electoral trial to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel failed to publish it within the time limits provided for in the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same 9th of November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Authority and described the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal" because he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge them".
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the IEM General Council it will be possible to achieve partial and total votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial countdown of votes, one or more electoral packages, may be: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of the voting and there is no record of the ballot in the ballot box; or there are obvious errors or alterations to the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all ballot ballots in the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the supposed winning candidate and the winner of the election in the second ballot is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and/or coalition who submitted the second of the nominated candidates.
The total countdown of the vote may also be achieved if, at the end of the common count, the difference between the supposed winning candidate and that of the second place is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party whose candidate has come out second, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of the partial countdown will be excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without recording the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
