MSS announces protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social Insurance conducts an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, known as the Protocol 'Genetics of Obesity for Children and Adolescents', which will allow for the overweight markers.
In a press release, Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry, Hospital of Specialities of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social assistants had been formed.
This team is supported by third-cycle specialists and students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Investigation and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) from the National Institute for Polytechnics (IPN).
In the investigation, it is invited to participate in the population with or without a right to participate in the sports units participating from IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is provided to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He pointed out that the protocol had begun in the Sporty Unit Cuauhtémoc (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October the activity took place in the Sporty Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the target of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Independencia (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Morelos (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and the objective of this investigation is to recognize the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on the World Diabetes Day, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or renal failure.
It was detailed that on Saturdays, all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (researching to identify people associated with childhood obesity) will be applied.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there was an increase in obesity of 77 per cent for boys and 47 per cent for girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight was also observed,' stressed the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search of markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others by its genetic history.
He informed that, on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of Indo-American inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics result in the inability to flush the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the full assessment of children, which helps to determine whether they are overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes disorders.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and physicians provide it to parents in writing, to which each of the measures and changes they must make in order to prevent disease are explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat paste with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM Asphalt Avoids Cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with a better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the paved was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of building and maintaining the tarp is adequate, the cassis could be completely reduced or even eliminated.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory of which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to that of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some northern cities of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore the formation of cassis.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbons, molecules with heavier molecular weight, called asphalts, and molecules with lower molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the paved its viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt is that at high temperatures of nearly 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes causative, it added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in their majority were covered by a flexible paved consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the little stones that forms the layer, it signals, is bathed in an asphalt year.
When vehicles pass through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well in the paved.
If we had modified asphalt, it would spread better, and the chemical engineer would.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a final layer is placed called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
As the part of the paved that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made of must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, as they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult to get it out, which brings back all layers of the paved and therefore causes cassis.
In the process of formation of a cassis, he says, the first one that breaks down is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the vehicle load is another important factor for the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the paved must always be linked to the load of the vehicle and guarantee its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still much to be done to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which already exist on the market in other countries and allow for easy repair of cassis without having to use high temperatures.
