Japan fell after the earthquake
GDP rose 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ended the decline spiral in early March
Since March the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, convalescent again after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, Japan's worst disaster since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government have calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have slowed down.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to finally turn the page: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and an annualised rate of 6%.
In addition, the second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes the highest rate of increase since January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and post-tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared with the decrease of 0.9% of capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of continuous increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, use the shortcomings to believe in zero.
Japan has awakened mainly as a result of developments in domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "values refuge" elected by investors who fled the debt crisis in the euro zone and the disordered forecasts of the United Nations, a privilege that weighs like a deal in the accounts of the exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of large technological groups.
