It is necessary to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says an expert committee
Canadians Live in Denial of Death, according to the Report of the Royal Society of Canada
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from various fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code so as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when necessary, with a patient who is deemed to be competent to make such a decision.
From the beginning of the game, the experts quote a recent survey of the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death".
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, reports the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, Quebec has the highest rate, with 86% of deaths occurring at the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report arrive at conclusions that run counter to the federal government's position, which has already said does not want to change the Criminal Code concerning euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also reviewed all countries where such approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-competent or unconsenting persons.
On the contrary, yesterday in the teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, there would be more cases of such spillovers precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assistant suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
