But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
It is that there is a fairly broad consensus between the left and the right on this issue.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who stated in 1976 that "900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate the whole misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared both on the left and on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is able to do so, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally paying; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book summarising the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limiting immigration anemia growth and employment.
The fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants may replace national workers, especially the low skilled, with a downward pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly engaged in occupations in sectors in which there is a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of employment.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows results in an increase between 0.6 and 0.9% of real wages in the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the US Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that in Germany, an immigrant at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (receipts less expenditure) of 150000 euros to public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished, at the beginning of the mandate, to go and find the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, in order to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
