North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia through the Baltic Sea, entered service.
It must provide gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a spark.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part, last Tuesday, on the Baltic coasts, between the orchestra and the end buffet, in the inauguration of Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly under the sea with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have taken together the wheel of the valve commander the entrance of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first 1 224 km tube linking the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction has air of victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
North Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries then lose a little power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to the western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare North Stream with a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has been able to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon by opening this gas pipeline, demonstrating how important the gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles shown by Gazprom's leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical exploitation.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-wrapped steel to protect it from anchors of ships.
It rests on the seabed, on average 200 m.
To build it, minefields dating back to World War II had to be avoided.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precautionary measure," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but project managers abandoned it while the Swedish were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently established off their coasts.
"In case of a tart, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to escape every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, carried by a ship, for external observation, and by a device operating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide of one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three complete days of travel at a speed of 3 meters a second, he provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo the slightest repair.
The flow of gas is simply controlled by pressure.
It's 200 bars at the start, and 100 bars at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, holding 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented the entire gas transport capacity to the company for 20 renewable years.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided at 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their fees, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy pine coast.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificity of the gas coming before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
