Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy set up in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is even higher than the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the general population.
Discourageing?
"No," said Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled."
" Progress has been considerable for fifteen years. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two or three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It must be said that for the disabled, there are still many obstacles before access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are more than 50 years old (17%) on average.
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bac and out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work, and which "are the crux of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's what we're doing for the target brakes.
Stay the unsaid, the attitudes that are changing, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Learning Association for the City indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "a overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment objective of 6% of disabled workers, laid down in a 1987 law.
The latest figures, which date back to 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of the Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on enterprises," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
